<div data-type="glossary"><h3 data-type="glossary-title">Glossary</h3>
<dl id="fs-idm122363760">
<dt>bicarbonate anion</dt>
<dd id="fs-idm120874064">salt of the hydrogen carbonate ion, <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mtext>HCO</mtext></mrow><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mrow/><mo>&#8722;</mo></msup></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><msub><mrow><mtext>HCO</mtext></mrow><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mrow/><mo>&#8722;</mo></msup></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math></dd>
</dl>
<dl id="fs-idm4412224">
<dt>carbonate</dt>
<dd id="fs-idm68673552">salt of the anion <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mtext>CO</mtext></mrow><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mrow/><mo>2&#8722;</mo></msup><mo>;</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><msub><mrow><mtext>CO</mtext></mrow><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mrow/><mo>2&#8722;</mo></msup><mo>;</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> often formed by the reaction of carbon dioxide with bases</dd>
</dl>
<dl id="fs-idm108042736">
<dt>hydrogen carbonate</dt>
<dd id="fs-idp29769440">salt of carbonic acid, H<sub>2</sub>CO<sub>3</sub> (containing the anion <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><semantics><mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mtext>HCO</mtext></mrow><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mrow/><mtext>&#8722;</mtext></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mrow><annotation-xml encoding="MathML-Content"><mrow><msub><mrow><mtext>HCO</mtext></mrow><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mrow/><mtext>&#8722;</mtext></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></annotation-xml></semantics></math> in which one hydrogen atom has been replaced; an acid carbonate; also known as <em data-effect="italics">bicarbonate ion</em></dd>
</dl>
